{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":951,"record_hash":"sha256:3094542902fa4b337b76f60080d18d24a7baef21f70f906b24ffeb32d1fec3f5","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:14:59.274Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"status\":{\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"This model is solid for both use cases, but it is more “evidence warehouse” than “product API” right now. That’s fine for planning, but v1 needs one clean read facade or UI work will get annoying fast.\\n\\n**Verdict**\\n\\nKeep: project-scoped sessions, capture turns, `TurnSummary`, `TurnDetail`, best-effort environment snapshots, and derived branch/review/change indexes.\\n\\nAdd now: explicit read shapes for the two product flows.\\n\\nRemove/defer: automatic numeric scoring details beyond confidence buckets. Store reasons, not fake precision.\\n\\n**What Works**\\n\\nSession handoff is well-supported. Turns give the next agent a usable timeline, and environment snapshots provide orientation without pretending a session belongs to a branch.\\n\\nReview sharing is also mostly supported. The key win is that branch/PR views can start from indexed observations, then highlight relevant turns inside a broader session. That is exactly the right model for GitButler’s multi-branch worktree reality.\\n\\nThe “persist observations, derive conclusions” stance is the right call. Durable ownership claims would age badly after rebases, squashes, stacked branch edits, or just normal human chaos.\\n\\n**Awkward Reads**\\n\\nThe current read path is too decomposed for product UI:\\n\\n- Handoff UI probably wants `getSessionTimeline(session_key, window?)`, not “read metadata, read turns list, read details, read records, maybe hydrate environment.”\\n- Review UI wants `findRelatedSessions(target)` returning sessions, highlighted turns, confidence, and reasons. It should not know about index verification, previous-turn matching, or scoring internals.\\n- `TurnSummary` may be too thin for timeline UI. It probably needs cheap display affordances: first user prompt preview, last assistant response preview, tool-call count, maybe provider turn grouping status. Otherwise every timeline row forces detail + record reads.\\n- Review sharing needs a “selected window” sha\n[TRUNCATED]\ntion to omit/hydrate them, especially for handoff where transcript readability matters more than branch evidence.\\n\\n**Add Now**\\n\\nAdd v1 read APIs/types before implementation hardens:\\n\\n```text\\nSessionTimeline {\\n  session,\\n  turns: TurnSummaryWithPreview[],\\n  has_more_before,\\n  has_more_after\\n}\\n\\nRelatedSessionResult {\\n  session_key,\\n  confidence,\\n  reasons,\\n  highlighted_turn_keys,\\n  suggested_turn_window,\\n  display_summary\\n}\\n```\\n\\nAlso add explicit target keys now:\\n\\n```text\\nbranch:<canonical-or-hashed-name>\\nreview:github-pr:<repo?>:<number>\\nchange:<change-id>\\ncommit:<sha>\\n```\\n\\nThe doc mentions branch/review key safety, but product APIs need canonical target identity or review lookup will become string soup.\\n\\nAdd privacy/export classification now. Review sharing is the risky use case. Prompts, tool calls, file paths, branch names, and environment snapshots can leak strategy or unrelated work. Even if repo access is assumed, shared web review links need a redaction/filtering story before this ships.\\n\\n**Remove Or Defer**\\n\\nDo not spend v1 energy on numeric `score: 82`. Use `high | medium | low | none` plus reasons. Numbers invite product arguments before there is real data.\\n\\nDo not expose `previous_turn_key` as a primary UI concept. It is useful for evidence computation, not user comprehension.\\n\\nDo not add path indexes in v1. The doc is right: too much write amplification and too many weird edge cases.\\n\\n**Main Product Risk**\\n\\nBackfill creates one giant capture turn. That is technically honest but product-awkward: first imported sessions may look like one blob. For handoff/review UI, provider turn grouping or record-level grouping needs to be good enough to render that blob sanely.\\n\\n**My Pick**\\n\\nShip this model, but define the read facades before storage lands. The storage plan is careful; the missing piece is making handoff and review sharing feel like first-class product queries instead of asking every UI to become a mini association engine.\"}},\"timed_out\":false}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:14:59.274Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}